path is the well-tested one

236
00:16:51,879 --> 00:16:57,179
When you get out, the other end
is sustainable AI velocity, fast

237
00:16:57,209 --> 00:17:02,799
enough to know fast enough to keep a
pace with the industry And reliable

238
00:17:02,819 --> 00:17:07,569
enough to trust with core production
workloads, and clear enough to

239
00:17:07,619 --> 00:17:10,709
keep the auditing or auditor happy.

240
00:17:11,209 --> 00:17:17,429
No maximum-- Not a maximum speed, not
maximum caution, but sustainable velocity.

241
00:17:17,929 --> 00:17:19,699
That is the design target

242
00:17:20,199 --> 00:17:20,489
Okay.

243
00:17:20,989 --> 00:17:25,559
I want to leave you with four
practical things you can do next week.

244
00:17:26,269 --> 00:17:31,059
No new budget just a standard
engineering discipline.

245
00:17:32,059 --> 00:17:33,589
Map your decision loops.

246
00:17:33,909 --> 00:17:39,289
Find every spot where a human is
wai- human is waiting on AI output

247
00:17:39,779 --> 00:17:42,549
or AI pipeline is waiting on a human.

248
00:17:43,209 --> 00:17:43,749
Time it.

249
00:17:44,169 --> 00:17:46,529
You will find hidden latency.

250
00:17:47,219 --> 00:17:50,549
You cannot fix what you cannot see.

251
00:17:51,049 --> 00:17:58,229
Give every LLM in production an owner,
not just your primary model, all of them.

252
00:17:58,999 --> 00:18:00,289
Identify the name.

253
00:18:00,519 --> 00:18:03,449
When I say the owner, its team.

254
00:18:04,059 --> 00:18:09,059
Who should-- who will own it, and who will
take accountability, and who will define

255
00:18:09,059 --> 00:18:12,289
the SLOs, and what is the escalation path?

256
00:18:12,789 --> 00:18:17,259
If you cannot answer these questions
for running model today, start there.

257
00:18:17,759 --> 00:18:20,929
Automate just one governance
decision this sprint.

258
00:18:21,789 --> 00:18:26,249
Find your highest volume
manual review setup write it

259
00:18:26,289 --> 00:18:28,079
as an automated policy rule.

260
00:18:28,619 --> 00:18:29,309
Ship it.

261
00:18:29,699 --> 00:18:31,569
Measure the latency delta.

262
00:18:32,169 --> 00:18:33,709
Build build out from there.

263
00:18:34,379 --> 00:18:35,149
Start from there.

264
00:18:35,149 --> 00:18:38,749
Document a single page golden path.

265
00:18:39,249 --> 00:18:45,119
For most common use cases, write
down the approved models, evaluation

266
00:18:45,119 --> 00:18:47,279
criteria, and security boundaries.

267
00:18:48,059 --> 00:18:51,379
Make it easier to follow than to ignore

268
00:18:51,879 --> 00:18:56,689
Distributed system engineering and
platform teams have been solving

269
00:18:56,729 --> 00:19:01,729
ownership, governance, and scale
problems for years We already have

270
00:19:01,729 --> 00:19:03,639
the tools and the mental models.

271
00:19:04,139 --> 00:19:08,819
The teams that successfully build
reliable LLM systems at scale will

272
00:19:08,889 --> 00:19:14,669
simply be the ones who treat human
decisions capa-capacity as a core design

273
00:19:14,669 --> 00:19:17,479
constraint rather than after a thought.

274
00:19:17,979 --> 00:19:19,779
Thank you very much for this opportunity.

275
00:19:20,619 --> 00:19:24,249
If you have any questions or if
you want to catch up after this

276
00:19:24,279 --> 00:19:26,709
conference, you can find me in LinkedIn.

277
00:19:27,449 --> 00:19:32,619
If you would like to read more about
my research papers on this area, you

278
00:19:32,619 --> 00:19:34,979
can find the articles from my website.

279
00:19:35,499 --> 00:19:35,879
Thank you.

